                            <container4_copy
                                cq:styleIds="[1653545847150,1653242825678,1653545825687,1653545835982]"
                                jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/container/v2/container">
                                <separator_copy_copy_
                                    cq:styleIds="[1662756423318]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-11-16T10:43:45.922-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="chiucx"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/separator/v2/separator"/>
                                <text_1091121937
                                    cq:styleIds="[1659545825678]"
                                    jcr:created="{Date}2022-12-07T05:33:30.724-05:00"
                                    jcr:createdBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:lastModified="{Date}2022-12-08T04:52:39.962-05:00"
                                    jcr:lastModifiedBy="kumarvx60"
                                    jcr:primaryType="nt:unstructured"
                                    sling:resourceType="abbvie-com2/components/text/v2/text"
                                    text="&lt;p>“We are doing a much better job today treating uterine fibroid symptoms with medication than we have done in the past,” Kumar says. “Some of our most exciting research focuses on reducing heavy menstrual bleeding in uterine fibroids patients.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Kumar mentions other studies focusing on topics such as:&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Genetic risk factors (for example, why fibroids occur more often in African-American women than in Caucasian women)&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Angiogenesis – the creation of blood vessels that “feed” fibroids&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Signaling pathways involved in the creation and growth of fibroids&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;li>Environmental factors and how they may influence the development of uterine fibroids&lt;/li>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;/ul>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“I was at a National Institute of Environmental Health Sciences conference recently on uterine fibroids, and I was blown away by all of the studies going on worldwide,” Kumar says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>More uterine fibroid patients are coming forward to share their stories, as well. Venable says when she started The Fibroid Foundation in 2012, she worked alone. “Now we have 26,000 members in 48 countries,” she says.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“That makes me hopeful,” she says. “When I started out this work, I thought, “I thought, ‘Who’s going to listen to you?’ It turned out to be a lot of people.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>Kumar advises women with symptoms to see a physician immediately, and not to be afraid to be open about their situation.&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;&lt;p>“You’re not being dramatic or exaggerating when you say, ‘I’m bleeding a lot,’” she says. “Heavy menstrual bleeding is defined by the impact it has on your quality of life. If it bothers you, then the physician should be listening.”&lt;/p>&#xd;&#xa;"
                                    textIsRich="true"/>
